{{chembox | Verifiedfields = changed | Watchedfields = changed | verifiedrevid = 460793987 | Name = Diquat dibromide | ImageFile = Diquat Structural Formula V1.svg | ImageAlt = Skeletal formula of diquat | ImageFile1 = Diquat dibromide 3D ball.png | ImageAlt1 = Ball-and-stick model of the component ions of diquat | IUPACName=6,7-Dihydrodipyrido[1,2-''a'':2′,1′-''c'']pyrazinediium dibromide | OtherNames=1,1′-Ethylene-2,2′-bipyridyldiylium dibromide |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}} | ChemSpiderID = 6536 | InChI = 1/C12H12N2.2BrH/c1-3-7-13-9-10-14-8-4-2-6-12(14)11(13)5-1;;/h1-8H,9-10H2;2*1H/q+2;;/p-2 | InChIKey = ODPOAESBSUKMHD-NUQVWONBAO | StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}} | StdInChI = 1S/C12H12N2.2BrH/c1-3-7-13-9-10-14-8-4-2-6-12(14)11(13)5-1;;/h1-8H,9-10H2;2*1H/q+2;;/p-2 | StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}} | StdInChIKey = ODPOAESBSUKMHD-UHFFFAOYSA-L | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}} | CASNo = 85-00-7 | PubChem=6794 | ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}} | ChEMBL = 1599022 | KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}} | KEGG = C18577 | UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}} | UNII = A9A615U4MP | SMILES = C1[n+]2ccccc2-c3cccc[n+]3C1.[Br-].[Br-] }} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | C=12 | H=12 | Br=2 | N=2 | Appearance=Yellow crystals<ref name=PGCH/> | Density=1.22–1.27&nbsp;g/cm<sup>3</sup> | MeltingPtC= 335 | BoilingPt= | BoilingPt_notes = Decomposes<ref name=PGCH/> | Solubility= 70% (20&nbsp;°C)<ref name=PGCH/> | VaporPressure = <{{val|0.00001|u=mmHg}} (20&nbsp;°C)<ref name=PGCH/> }} |Section3={{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards= | FlashPt= | AutoignitionPt = | PEL = none<ref name=PGCH>{{PGCH|0243}}</ref> | IDLH = N.D.<ref name=PGCH/> | REL = TWA 0.5&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup><ref name=PGCH/> }} }}
'''Diquat''' is a contact [[herbicide]] that produces [[desiccation]] and [[defoliation]] most often available as the dibromide, '''diquat dibromide'''.<ref>''Merck Index'', 11th Edition, '''3359'''.</ref> Brand names for this formulation include Aquacide, Dextrone, Preeglone, Deiquat, Spectracide, Detrone, Reglone, Reglon, Reglox, Tribune, Ortho-Diquat, Weedtrine-D,<ref>[https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?cid=6794 PubChem listing for diquat dibromide]</ref> Weedol 2, and in combination with [[glyphosate]], Resolva.<ref name=rhs>[http://www.rhs.org.uk/media/pdfs/advice/WeedkillersForGardeners Weedkillers for Home Gardeners]. RHS Advisory Service, ''Royal Horticultural Society'', February 2013. Accessed May 2013.</ref>
Diquat is a nonselective herbicide that acts quickly to damage only those parts of the plant to which it is applied.<ref name="extoxnet">[http://pmep.cce.cornell.edu/profiles/extoxnet/dienochlor-glyphosate/diquat-ext.html EXTOXNET], Pesticide Information Project</ref> It has been used in pre-harvest [[crop desiccation]].<ref name=moneuro>{{cite web | url=http://www.monsanto.com/products/Documents/glyphosate-background-materials/Agronomic%20benefits%20of%20glyphosate%20in%20Europe.pdf | title=The agronomic benefits of glyphosate in Europe | publisher=[[Monsanto]] Europe SA | date=February 2010 | accessdate=June 2, 2013 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117143642/http://www.monsanto.com/products/Documents/glyphosate-background-materials/Agronomic%20benefits%20of%20glyphosate%20in%20Europe.pdf | archivedate=January 17, 2012 | df= }}</ref> It bonds strongly to mineral and organic particles in soil and water, where it remains without significant degradation for years. However, bound to clays, diquat is biologically inactive at concentrations typically observed in agricultural soils.<ref name="extoxnet"></ref>
Diquat dibromide is moderately toxic. It may be fatal to humans if swallowed, inhaled, or absorbed through the skin in large quantities.<ref name="extoxnet"/>
==Production== [[Pyridine]] is oxidatively coupled to [[2,2'-Bipyridine|2,2′-bipyridine]] over a heated [[Raney nickel]] catalyst. The ethylene bridge is formed by the reaction with [[1,2-dibromoethane]]:<ref>{{cite web | title = Paraquat and Diquat | publisher = [[IPCS INCHEM]] | url = http://www.inchem.org/documents/ehc/ehc/ehc39.htm}}</ref>
