'''Eastern Alberta Transmission Line''' is a 485&nbsp;km long, 500 kV, bipolar, [[high-voltage direct current]], overhead [[Electric power transmission|transmission line]] interconnecting Newell HVDC static inverter plant near Brooks, Alberta with Heathfield static inverter plant near Gibbons, Alberta - northeast of Edmonton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atcoelectric.com/Projects/HVDC/Project-Details/ |title=Project Details  |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2013 |publisher=[[ATCO Electric]] |accessdate=2014-08-05}}</ref> The transmission line includes 1387 [[Transmission tower|transmission towers]] and the construction of the 500kV DC transmission line is completed since december 2014 at a total cost of C$1.8&nbsp;billion. Work continues on the EATL converter stations. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atcoelectric.com/Projects/HVDC/Eastern-Alberta-Transmission-Line |title=Eastern Alberta Transmission Line |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2013 |publisher=[[ATCO Electric]] |accessdate=2014-08-05}}</ref> The project is the first newly built, long-distance, HVDC line in Canada since the completion of the [[Quebec – New England Transmission]] Project, and is owned by [[ATCO Electric]], being built by [[Siemens]]. See also '''Western Alberta Transmission Line''' (WATL).<br>
Eastern Alberta Transmission Line uses as Western Alberta Transmission Line in opposite to other HVDC schemes as [[Nelson River Bipole]] an insulated, metallic conductor for the neutral pole, in order to avoid any risk of electrochemical corrosion of oil and gas pipelines.

