{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country= |Ship flag= |Ship name=*''Zlatograd'' (1973–99) *''Loti'' (1999–2002) *''Dora'' (2002–03) *''Shelly'' (2003–07) |Ship namesake= [[Zlatograd]], [[Bulgaria]] (1973–99) |Ship owner= |Ship operator= |Ship route= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder= Ivan Dimitrov shipyard, [[Ruse, Bulgaria]] |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= 15 |Ship laid down= |Ship launched= |Ship completed= 1973 |Ship acquired= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship registry=*{{flagicon|Bulgaria}} (1973–?) *{{flagicon|Slovakia}} (?–2007) |Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|7306673}} *[[Call sign#Ships and boats|call sign]] OMJB *{{ICS|Oscar}}{{ICS|Mike}}{{ICS|Juliet}}{{ICS|Bravo}} |Ship fate= sank after collision 30 August 2007 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship type= |Ship tonnage= {{GRT|1837}} |Ship displacement= |Ship length= {{convert|80.8|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam= {{convert|11.9|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draught= |Ship depth= |Ship decks= |Ship power= |Ship propulsion= [[Marine propulsion#Reciprocating diesel engines|diesel engine]], single [[Propeller|screw]] |Ship speed= {{convert|12|kn|km/h}} |Ship capacity= |Ship crew= |Ship armament= |Ship sensors= |Ship notes= }} |}
'''MV ''Shelly''''' was a {{GRT|1837}} [[cargo ship]] that was built in [[Bulgaria]] in 1973. She sank off the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] coast of [[Israel]] in 2007 after the {{GRT|10392}} [[cruise ship]] {{ship|CS|Salamis Glory}} rammed her and broke her in two. Two of ''Shelly''{{'}}s crew were killed.
==Ship== The Ivan Dimitrov shipyard<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?30905 |title=MV Shelly [+2007] |last=Allen |first=Tony |date=27 January 2014 |work=WreckSite |publisher=wrecksite.eu |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> on the River [[Danube]] in [[Ruse, Bulgaria]] built the ship and launched her in 1973 as ''Zlatograd''. She changed hands in 1999 and was renamed ''Loti''. She changed hands again in 2002 and was renamed ''Dora''. In 2003 Israeli owners bought her, renamed her ''Shelly'' and [[Ship registration|registered]] her in [[Slovakia]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.shipspotting.com/gallery/photo.php?lid=17363 |last=Kermen |first=Ilhan |title=Zlatograd – IMO 7306673 |publisher=Shipspotting.com |date=14 June 2008 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> She was crewed not by Israelis but by other nationalities,<ref name=WashPost>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/31/AR2007083100575.html |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Israeli Divers Find Bodies of 2 Sailors |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=31 August 2007 |accessdate=3 September 2007}}</ref> mainly Slovaks and [[Ukraine|Ukrainians]].<ref name=Haaretz/>
==Collision and sinking== On 30 August 2007, ''Shelly'' was at anchor about {{convert|3|km|nmi|disp=flip}} off Israeli coast, near the [[port of Haifa]], when at about 10pm she was accidentally rammed by the [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] passenger ship ''Salamis Glory'', which had left port at Haifa several minutes before.<ref name=WashPost/><ref name=Haaretz>{{cite news |url= http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/899674.html |last1=Eyadat |first1=Fadi |last2=Azoulay |first2=Yuval |title=Rescuers retrieve bodies of two sailors killed in collision off Haifa |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |date=1 September 2007 |accessdate=3 September 2007}}</ref> ''Shelly'' sank quickly after the collision, which the [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]] said broke her in half.<ref name=J-Post>{{cite news |url= http://www.jpost.com/Israel/Bodies-of-missing-seamen-found-after-Haifa-ship-collision |last=Leshem |first=Elie |title=Bodies of missing seamen found after Haifa ship collision |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=30 August 2007 |accessdate=3 September 2007}}</ref> 11 crew members escaped, and most climbed aboard a rescue launch lowered by ''Salamis Glory'' and were subsequently rescued by the [[Israeli Navy]].<ref name=WashPost/> The rest were rescued by helicopter.<ref name=Haaretz/> The survivors refused to be taken to a local hospital for treatment.<ref name=Haaretz/> ''Salamis Glory'' subsequently returned to port in Haifa, showing slight damage to her hull.<ref name=WashPost/> None of ''Salamis Glory''{{'}}s 700 or so passengers and crew was injured.<ref name=Haaretz/>
The remaining two crew members were declared missing, prompting a search and rescue operation involving six naval vessels, multiple aircraft and divers.<ref name=Haaretz/> 12 hours after the sinking their bodies were recovered from the wreck by divers<ref name=WashPost/> in {{convert|20|m}} of water.<ref name=J-Post/> The dead were identified as the ship's [[Indonesia]]n [[Chief mate|First Mate]] and Ukrainian [[Chief engineer|engineer]].<ref name=Haaretz/>
The vessel's sinking released an [[oil spill]] that moved down the coast, causing authorities to warn the public not to bathe at the nearby Zevulun beach.<ref name=Haaretz/>
On 31 August Salamis Lines, owners of ''Salamis Glory'', arranged for 148 stranded Cypriot passengers from the ship to be flown back to Cyprus on a [[Cyprus Airways]] jet.<ref name=Haaretz/><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.cyprus-mail.com/news/main.php?id=34469&cat_id=1 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202840/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/news/main.php?id=34469&cat_id=1 |dead-url= yes |archive-date= 27 September 2007 |last=Leonidou |first=Leo |title=Cruise passengers return home after accident |newspaper=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=3 September 2007}}</ref>
==Investigation== [[Israeli Police]] launched a full investigation into the cause of the accident, aided by Cypriot authorities.<ref name=WashPost/> All of ''Salamis Glory''{{'}}s crew were interviewed. One possibility being considered was that there was a fault in the ship's navigation system,<ref name=WashPost/> with some reports of a loss of steering control aboard ''Salamis Glory''.<ref name=Haaretz/>
