[[Fluorine]] forms [[diatomic molecule]]s ({{chem|F|2}}) that are gaseous at room temperature with a density about 1.3 times that of air.{{sfn|Jaccaud et al.|2005|p=2}}{{#tag:ref|Density of air at 100&nbsp;[[kilopascal]] and 0&nbsp;°C is 1.2724&nbsp;g/L.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shelquist |first=Richard |year=2010 |title=An introduction to air density and density altitude calculations|url = http://wahiduddin.net/calc/density_altitude.htm|publisher=Shelquist Engineering|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>|group="note"}} Though sometimes cited as yellow-green, pure fluorine gas is actually a very pale yellow. The color can only be observed in concentrated fluorine gas when looking down the axis of long tubes, as it appears transparent when observed from the side in normal tubes or if allowed to escape into the atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Burdon | first1 = J. | last2 = Emson | first2 = B. | last3 = Edwards | first3 = A. J. | doi = 10.1016/S0022-1139(00)85188-X | title = Is Fluorine Gas Really Yellow? | journal = Journal of Fluorine Chemistry | volume = 34 | issue = 3–4 | pages = 471 | year = 1987 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref> The element has a "pungent" characteristic odor that is noticeable in concentrations as low as 20&nbsp;[[parts per billion|ppb]].{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}

[[File:Moissan color images.jpg|thumb|500px|center|1892 observation of the color of fluorine gas by [[Henri Moissan]], who first isolated the element, using end-view on 5 meter long tubes.  Air (1) is on the left, fluorine (2) is in the middle, chlorine (3) is on the right.]]

[[File:Liquid fluorine tighter crop.jpg|thumb|Liquid fluorine]]

Fluorine condenses to a bright yellow liquid at −188&nbsp;°C (−307&nbsp;°F),{{sfn|Dean|1999|p=523}} which is near the condensation temperatures of oxygen and nitrogen.  <!--- add density, heat capacity info-->

The solid state of fluorine relies on [[Van der Waals force]]s to hold molecules together,{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}} which, because of the small size of the [[fluorine]] molecules, are relatively weak. Consequently, the solid state of fluorine is more similar to that of oxygen or the noble gases than to those of the heavier halogens.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}
[[File:Beta-fluorine_crystal_structure.gif|thumb|Animation showing the crystal structure of beta-fluorine.]]

Fluorine solidifies at −220&nbsp;°C (−363&nbsp;°F){{sfn|Dean|1999|p=523}} into a [[Cubic crystal system|cubic]] structure, called beta-fluorine. This [[phase (matter)|phase]] is transparent and soft, with significant disorder of the molecules; its density is 1.70&nbsp;g/cm<sup>3</sup>. At −228&nbsp;°C (−378&nbsp;°F) fluorine undergoes a solid–solid [[phase transition]] into a [[monoclinic crystal system|monoclinic]] structure called alpha-fluorine. This phase is opaque and hard, with close-packed layers of molecules, and is denser at 1.97&nbsp;g/cm<sup>3</sup>.<ref>http://jcp.aip.org/resource/1/jcpsa6/v49/i4/p1902_s1</ref> The solid state phase change requires more energy than the melting point transition and can be violent, shattering samples and blowing out sample holder windows.<ref name="phases">{{cite report|last=Young|first=David A.|publisher=Springer|title=Phase Diagrams of the Elements|page=10|year=1975|url=http://www.osti.gov/bridge/servlets/purl/4010212-0BbwUC/4010212.pdfaccess|accessdate=2016-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Barrett | first1 = C. S.| last2 = Meyer | first2 = L.| last3 = Wasserman | first3 = J.| title = Argon—Fluorine Phase Diagram | doi = 10.1063/1.1711946 | journal = The Journal of Chemical Physics | volume = 47 | issue = 2 | pages = 740–743 | year = 1967|bibcode = 1967JChPh..47..740B }}</ref>
<!--- add density, heat capacity info-->

Solid fluorine received significant study in the 1920s and 30s, but relatively less until the 1960s. The crystal structure of alpha-fluorine given, which still has some uncertainty, dates to a 1970 paper by [[Linus Pauling]].

